  TO TAKE A MINUTE?             

225
00:09:31,438 --> 00:09:34,506
                 IT'S FINE.     
 I JUST WANT TO GET OUT OF HERE.

226
00:09:34,508 --> 00:09:35,607
        OKAY.                   

227
00:09:41,515 --> 00:09:45,784
FOR A MOMENT, I REALLY FELT LIKE
THINGS WERE DIFFERENT.          

228
00:09:45,786 --> 00:09:47,452
  BUT THEY'RE NOT.              

229
00:09:47,454 --> 00:09:50,121
NO MATTER WHERE I GO,           
    I'M TRAPPED.                

230
00:09:50,123 --> 00:09:51,556
               BUT YOU'RE NOT.  

231
00:09:51,558 --> 00:09:54,259
          YOU'RE NOT UNDERWATER,
         YOU'RE NOT IN A MIRROR.

232
00:09:54,261 --> 00:09:55,927
         THIS TIME, YOU'RE FREE!

233
00:09:55,929 --> 00:09:57,529
BUT I'M STILL ON EARTH.         

234
00:09:57,531 --> 00:10:00,131
      YEAH, BUT NOTHING IS<i> STILL</i>
                  ON EARTH.     

235
00:10:00,133 --> 00:10:01,967
                EVERYTHING'S    
              ALWAYS CHANGING.  

236
00:10:01,969 --> 00:10:03,702
                THE LEAVES...   

237
00:10:03,704 --> 00:10:04,869
                THE CITIES...   

238
00:10:04,871 --> 00:10:07,138
      [ CAR HORNS HONKING ]     
            EVEN JERSEY CHANGES.

239
00:10:07,140 --> 00:10:09,574
      MY DAD SAYS THE REST STOPS
        USED TO BE PRETTY GROSS,

240
00:10:09,576 --> 00:10:11,109
        BUT NOW THEY HAVE SUSHI!

241
00:10:11,111 --> 00:10:13,445
       THIS ISN'T THE SAME WORLD
       THAT HELD YOU PRISONER --

242
00:10:13,447 --> 00:10:16,414
         NOT ANYMORE, AND I KNOW
      IT DOESN'T FEEL LIKE HOME,

243
00:10:16,416 --> 00:10:19,050
                  BUT MAYBE     
           THAT CAN CHANGE, TOO.

244
00:10:22,823 --> 00:10:25,123
  I KNOW YOU CAN'T              
GO BACK TO HOMEWORLD,           

245
00:10:25,125 --> 00:10:26,658
BUT IF YOU STAY HERE...         

246
00:10:26,660 --> 00:10:29,461
IT'LL BE YOUR CHOICE            
    TO STAY HERE.               

247
00:10:30,897 --> 00:10:32,230
                 IT'S FUNNY.    

248
00:10:32,232 --> 00:10:33,598
              FOR ALL THE TIME  
              I SPENT ON EARTH, 

249
00:10:33,600 --> 00:10:36,001
         I BARELY SAW ANY OF IT.

250
00:10:36,003 --> 00:10:37,235
  THAT'S NOT FUNNY.             

251
00:10:37,237 --> 00:10:39,037
  THAT'S SUPER SAD.             

252
00:10:40,674 --> 00:10:42,107
                    I...        

253
00:10:42,109 --> 00:10:43,775
              I WANT TO SEE IT. 

254
00:10:43,777 --> 00:10:44,442
        YEAH?                   

255
00:10:44,444 --> 00:10:46,144
            I WANT TO STAY HERE.

256
00:10:46,146 --> 00:10:48,913
        HERE?                   
  LIKE,<i> HERE</i> HERE?              

257
00:10:48,915 --> 00:10:50,515
              YEAH,<i> HERE</i> HERE!  

258
00:10:50,517 --> 00:10:53,318
  YES, HEAR, HEAR,              
     EVERYBODY!                 

259
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:55,754
     WHAT ARE WE                
   TALKING ABOUT?               

260
00:10:55,756 --> 00:10:56,821
                    YOU?!       

261
00:10:56,823 --> 00:10:59,457
LAZULI, NICE TO SEE YOU         
    UP AND ABOUT.               

262
00:10:59,459 --> 00:11:01,626
                WHAT ARE<i> YOU</i>    
                DOING HERE?!    

263
00:11:01,628 --> 00:11:04,529
 THIS IS MY NEW HOME            
AWAY FROM HOMEWORLD!            

264
00:11:04,531 --> 00:11:06,865
                NO, IT'S NOT!   
                 IT'S<i> MINE!</i>     

265
00:11:06,867 --> 00:11:07,999
               RIGHT, STEVEN?   

266
00:11:08,001 --> 00:11:09,367
              UH...             

267
00:11:09,369 --> 00:11:10,902
            OH, BOY.            

268
00:11:13,540 --> 00:11:16,107
      [ INSECTS CHIRPING ]      

269
00:11:29,523 --> 00:11:32,624
   Peridot: AND THEN I'LL SAY,  
"HEY, AS ONE REFUGEE TO ANOTHER,

270
00:11:32,626 --> 00:11:35,694
   IT ISN'T SO BAD THAT WE CAN  
   NEVER GO BACK TO HOMEWORLD,  

271
00:11:35,696 --> 00:11:36,728
           AM I RIGHT?          

272
00:11:36,730 --> 00:11:38,196
       WHY DON'T WE WATCH       
         THE SUN COME UP        

273
00:11:38,198 --> 00:11:40,031
         AND FIGURE OUT         
     WHAT WE'RE GOING TO DO     

274
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:41,533
       WITH ALL THIS TIME,      
          EH, LAZULI?"          

275
00:11:41,535 --> 00:11:43,301
      AND THEN SHE'LL SAY,      
         "YES, PERIDOT.         

276
00:11:43,303 --> 00:11:45,203
  AS IMPRESSED AS I WAS BY YOU  
          ON THE SHIP,          

277
00:11:45,205 --> 00:11:47,138
    I AM EVEN MORE IMPRESSED    
   WITH YOUR NEW COMPACT LOOK   

278
00:11:47,140 --> 00:11:48,573
  AND CAPACITY FOR FRIENDSHIP.  

279
00:11:48,575 --> 00:11:51,409
     I'M SO GLAD WE'RE GOING    
     TO BE LIVING TOGETHER."    

280
00:11:51,411 --> 00:11:53,645
            PERIDOT.            
           FACET FIVE.          

281
00:11:53,647 --> 00:11:54,913
            [ CLICK ]           

282
00:11:54,915 --> 00:11:56,414
          LET'S BEGIN.          

283
00:11:56,416 --> 00:11:58,183
          THIS ISN'T GONNA WORK.

284
00:11:58,185 --> 00:12:00,418
           WAIT, WHAT?          

285
00:12:00,420 --> 00:12:02,887
     I REALLY THOUGHT I WOULD BE
             LIVING ALONE HERE. 

286
00:12:02,889 --> 00:12:04,489
        YEAH,                   
BUT THIS IS EVEN BETTER.        

287
00:12:04,491 --> 00:12:06,057
      OH, HERE,                 
   HOW ABOUT THIS?              

288
00:12:06,059 --> 00:12:08,159
I SAW THIS ON AN EPISODE        
    OF A TV SHOW.               

289
00:12:08,161 --> 00:12:09,394
I DIDN'T SEE HOW IT ENDED,      

290
00:12:09,396 --> 00:12:11,329
    BUT I'M SURE                
IT WORKED OUT GREAT.            

291
00:12:11,331 --> 00:12:13,164
    WE'LL DIVIDE                
 THIS PLACE IN HALF.            

292
00:12:13,166 --> 00:12:14,733
  YOU'LL BOTH HAVE              
   YOUR OWN SPACE.              

293
00:12:14,735 --> 00:12:16,501
   HIGH CEILINGS,               
  REAL WOOD FLOORS,             

294
00:12:16,503 --> 00:12:19,037
CONVENIENT LOCATION IN THE HEART
   OF THE COUNTRY.              

295
00:12:19,039 --> 00:12:20,839
SO WHAT DO YA THINK,            
      ROOMIES?                  

296
00:12:22,442 --> 00:12:25,243
I LIKE THE CUT OF YOUR GEM,     
   STEVEN QUARTZ.               

297
00:12:25,245 --> 00:12:27,178
                 NO. NO WAY!    

298
00:12:27,180 --> 00:12:28,546
 WHAT'S THE PROBLEM?            

299
00:12:28,548 --> 00:12:30,448
     YOU'RE THE ONE GETTING     
       ALL THE GOOD STUFF!      

300
00:12:30,450 --> 00:12:33,418
    YOU'VE GOT THE PROPELLER    
  AND PAINT CANS ON YOUR SIDE!  

301
00:12:33,420 --> 00:12:34,853
         YOU CAN DO TONS        
           WITH THOSE!          

302
00:12:34,855 --> 00:12:37,288
    OOH, ACTUALLY, I KIND OF    
      WANT THE PAINT CANS.      

303
00:12:37,290 --> 00:12:38,890
            YOU WANT            
       TO TRADE SOMETHING?      

304
00:12:38,892 --> 00:12:41,793
                I DON'T CARE    
              ABOUT PAINT CANS. 

305
00:12:41,795 --> 00:12:43,862
         THAT'S NOT THE PROBLEM.

306
00:12:43,864 --> 00:12:44,896
              BAH.              

307
00:12:44,898 --> 00:12:46,097
WHAT'S WRONG, LAPIS?            

308
00:12:46,099 --> 00:12:47,532
                  IT'S<i> HER.</i>     

309
00:12:47,534 --> 00:12:48,366
              UGH!              

310
00:12:48,368 --> 00:12:49,901
             SHE'S THE PROBLEM! 

311
00:12:49,903 --> 00:12:52,203
    I CAN'T STAND THE THOUGHT OF
HAVING TO LOOK AT HER EVERY DAY.

312
00:12:52,205 --> 00:12:54,239
    SHE'S THE ONE WHO DRAGGED ME
               BACK TO EARTH.   

313
00:12:54,241 --> 00:12:56,541
     HEY, IT WASN'T MY IDEA.    

314
00:12:56,543 --> 00:12:58,710
     I WAS HEADED TO EARTH,     
   AND I NEEDED AN INFORMANT.   

315
00:12:58,712 --> 00:13:00,545
       IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN      
        A SIMPLE MISSION.       

316
00:13:00,547 --> 00:13:03,448
 THINGS DIDN'T EXACTLY WORK OUT 
        FOR EITHER OF US.       

317
00:13:03,450 --> 00:13:05,717
                 YOU USED ME    
         LIKE EVERYONE ELSE DID!

318
00:13:05,719 --> 00:13:07,719
          BUT IT'S NOT          
       LIKE THAT ANYMORE.       

319
00:13:07,721 --> 00:13:08,887
       IT'S DIFFERENT NOW.      

320
00:13:08,889 --> 00:13:10,088
         <i> I'M</i> DIFFERENT.        

321
00:13:10,090 --> 00:13:11,422
  IT'S TRUE, LAPIS.             

322
00:13:11,424 --> 00:13:13,258
 PERIDOT HAS REALLY             
  COME INTO HER OWN             

323
00:13:13,260 --> 00:13:14,993
SINCE SHE'S BEEN LIVING         
      ON EARTH.                 

324
00:13:14,995 --> 00:13:17,061
           I SABOTAGED          
         MY OWN MISSION!        

325
00:13:17,063 --> 00:13:18,596
    I HELPED SAVE THE EARTH!    

326
00:13:18,598 --> 00:13:20,331
          I EVEN YELLED         
       AT YELLOW DIAMOND!       

327
00:13:20,333 --> 00:13:22,233
     SHE'S PROBABLY SENDING     
          A WHOLE FLEET         

328
00:13:22,235 --> 00:13:24,068
           TO FIND ME           
    AND SHATTER ME RIGHT NOW!   

329
00:13:24,070 --> 00:13:25,904
     I'M KIND OF A BIG DEAL.    

330
00:13:25,906 --> 00:13:27,972
   A BIG, ANTI-HOMEWORLD DEAL!  

331
00:13:29,009 --> 00:13:32,610
           STEVEN, I DON'T THINK
             THIS IS GONNA WORK.

332
00:13:32,612 --> 00:13:36,648
    UH, UM, MAYBE               
WE COULD PUT UP A CURTAIN?      

333
00:13:42,923 --> 00:13:44,789
     ER, SORRY.                 

334
00:13:44,791 --> 00:13:47,125
 I THOUGHT THIS WAS             
   GONNA BE OKAY.               

335
00:13:47,127 --> 00:13:50,962
I FORGOT THAT THE LAST TIME YOU 
SAW EACH OTHER<i> WASN'T</i> SO OKAY.  

336
00:13:50,964 --> 00:13:52,497
           THAT WAS IN THE PAST.

337
00:13:52,499 --> 00:13:54,532
         IT'S NOT LIKE THAT NOW!

338
00:13:54,534 --> 00:13:55,600
                    AGGH!       

339
00:13:55,602 --> 00:13:56,534
       I KNOW.                  

340
00:13:56,536 --> 00:13:58,503
                BUT OBVIOUSLY   
                SHE DOESN'T.    

341
00:13:58,505 --> 00:14:00,438
                SHE'S THE ONE   
             THAT NEEDS TO KNOW!

342
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:02,540
       I WANT<i> HER</i> TO UNDERSTAND.

343
00:14:02,542 --> 00:14:05,109
AW, PERIDOT, THAT'S SWEET.      

344
00:14:05,111 --> 00:14:07,278
  THAT'S THE "YOU"              
YOU NEED TO SHOW HER.           

345
00:14:07,280 --> 00:14:09,814
             SHOW HER MY SWEET? 

346
00:14:09,816 --> 00:14:11,282
     I GOT YOU.                 

347
00:14:11,284 --> 00:14:13,484
CARDS ARE A GREAT WAY           
TO TELL SOMEONE SOMETHING       

348
00:14:13,486 --> 00:14:15,453
IF YOU CAN'T BE FACE-TO-FACE    
     WITH THEM.                 

349
00:14:15,455 --> 00:14:17,155
OR IF THEY DON'T WANT           
  TO SEE YOUR FACE.             

350
00:14:17,157 --> 00:14:21,392
YOU'VE GOT TO GIVE HER A TASTE  
OF THE SWEET VERSION OF PERIDOT.

351
00:14:21,394 --> 00:14:24,195
     HERE, LOOK.                

352
00:14:24,197 --> 00:14:27,732
 IT'S YOU AND LAPIS             
   HOLDING HANDS!               

353
00:14:27,734 --> 00:14:29,467
            WHERE ARE OUR NOSES?

354
00:14:29,469 --> 00:14:31,402
OH, THAT'S KIND OF PART         
 OF MY STYLE LATELY.            

355
00:14:31,404 --> 00:14:34,305
           IS NOT HAVING FINGERS
              ALSO YOUR STYLE?  

356
00:14:34,307 --> 00:14:36,407
NO, I'M -- I'M JUST BAD         
  AT DRAWING HANDS.             

357
00:14:36,409 --> 00:14:38,343
UH, SO HERE'S YOUR PART.        
     COME HERE.                 

358
00:14:38,345 --> 00:14:39,978
WRITE AN APOLOGY INSIDE         
      TO LAPIS                  

359
00:14:39,980 --> 00:14:42,480
SO SHE KNOWS HOW SORRY YOU WERE 
    ABOUT BEFORE,               

360
00:14:42,482 --> 00:14:44,315
 AND THAT EVERYTHING            
    IS OKAY NOW.                

361
00:14:44,317 --> 00:14:46,251
   IF YOU WRITE IT              
  FROM YOUR HEART,              

362
00:14:46,253 --> 00:14:48,386
    YOUR FEELINGS               
   WILL REACH HER.              

363
00:14:50,824 --> 00:14:52,690
JUST TRY TO BE SINCERE.         

364
00:14:52,692 --> 00:14:54,759
                    HMM.        

365
00:14:56,229 --> 00:14:57,929
            [ SIGHS ]           

366
00:14:57,931 --> 00:14:59,497
Peridot: HEY, LAZULI!           

367
00:14:59,499 --> 00:15:01,866
    HEY, LAZULI!                
        HEY!                    

368
00:15:01,868 --> 00:15:03,768
                    UGH.        
LAZULI!                         

369
00:15:03,770 --> 00:15:04,569
        HEY!                    

370
00:15:04,571 --> 00:15:06,537
       WHY ISN'T SHE RESPONDING?

371
00:15:06,539 --> 00:15:09,440
    I'M NOT SURE.               
I THOUGHT SHE WAS UP THERE.     

372
00:15:09,442 --> 00:15:11,342
LAPIS?                          
              HUH?              

373
00:15:11,344 --> 00:15:12,377
  ARE YOU UP THERE?             

374
00:15:12,379 --> 00:15:14,846
    YES, STEVEN?                

375
00:15:14,848 --> 00:15:16,447
             GO ON.             

376
00:15:18,551 --> 00:15:20,885
         STEVEN DID THE OUTSIDE,

377
00:15:20,887 --> 00:15:22,620
           AND I DID THE INSIDE.

378
00:15:22,622 --> 00:15:25,690
"SORRY I INTERROGATED YOU.      

379
00:15:25,692 --> 00:15:28,426
YOU WERE JUST FULL OF           
SUCH USEFUL INFORMATION.        

380
00:15:28,428 --> 00:15:30,728
  THAT'S A SINCERE              
     COMPLIMENT.                

381
00:15:30,730 --> 00:15:33,598
      PERIDOT."                 

382
00:15:34,868 --> 00:15:36,200
                 THE NOSES!     

383
00:15:36,202 --> 00:15:38,870
           ONE CAN ONLY CONCLUDE
  THAT IT WAS THE LACK OF NOSES!

384
00:15:38,872 --> 00:15:40,104
        IT SEEMS ILLOGICAL TO ME

385
00:15:40,106 --> 00:15:42,040
         THAT IT WOULD BE ANY OF
           THE WRITING ELEMENTS.

386
00:15:42,042 --> 00:15:44,042
         IT TOOK ME OVER AN HOUR
               TO COMPOSE IT,   

387
00:15:44,044 --> 00:15:46,811
     AND I WAS<i> THE</i> MOST SINCERE,
   AS PER STEVEN'S INSTRUCTIONS.

388
00:15:46,813 --> 00:15:49,314
IT COULD BE SHE'S JUST          
NOT MUCH OF A READER?           

389
00:15:49,316 --> 00:15:50,315
  HOW ABOUT A GIFT?             

390
00:15:50,317 --> 00:15:51,482
              ANOTHER APPROACH. 

391
00:15:51,484 --> 00:15:53,718
               YES. BUT WHAT?   

392
00:15:53,720 --> 00:15:56,387
        HMM.                    
THINK OF THINGS SHE LIKES.      

393
00:15:56,389 --> 00:15:57,889
              THINGS SHE LIKES. 

394
00:15:57,891 --> 00:16:01,592
     LAPIS LAZULIS ARE TYPICALLY
    PARTIAL TO WATER AND FLYING.

395
00:16:01,594 --> 00:16:02,727
                    HMM.        

396
00:16:02,729 --> 00:16:03,428
                     AH!        

397
00:16:03,430 --> 00:16:04,395
      [ GASPS ]                 

398
00:16:04,397 --> 00:16:05,964
                     NO.        

399
00:16:05,966 --> 00:16:07,398
         NO?                    

400
00:16:07,400 --> 00:16:08,733
                   NUH-UH.      

401
00:16:08,735 --> 00:16:09,767
                   BUT IF!      

402
00:16:09,769 --> 00:16:10,835
        YEAH?                   

403
00:16:10,837 --> 00:16:12,303
                    NAH.        

404
00:16:12,305 --> 00:16:15,440
YEAH, THAT'D PROBABLY BE        
    OVERDOING IT.               

405
00:16:15,442 --> 00:16:17,241
          [ BOTH SIGH ]         

406
00:16:17,243 --> 00:16:18,977
        HMM.                    

407
00:16:18,979 --> 00:16:20,745
             WATER.             

408
00:16:20,747 --> 00:16:23,781
   I THINK YOU HAVE SOMETHING   
           WITH THAT.           

409
00:16:23,783 --> 00:16:26,751
    YOU CAN'T SEE THROUGH THOSE,
                   RIGHT?       

410
00:16:26,753 --> 00:16:29,854
   ACTUALLY, YES.               
BUT IT'S VERY BLURRY.           

411
00:16:29,856 --> 00:16:31,122
                GOOD TO KNOW.   

412
00:16:31,124 --> 00:16:33,491
             WELL, HERE WE ARE! 

413
00:16:33,493 --> 00:16:35,860
        H-2 OH, MY GOSH!        

414
00:16:35,862 --> 00:16:38,830
         IT'S A SMALLER         
       THAN AVERAGE LAKE!       

415
00:16:38,832 --> 00:16:40,498
       IT'S FROM THE HOLE       
        WHEN WE DRILLED.        

416
00:16:40,500 --> 00:16:42,867
     PERIDOT AND I SEALED IT    
    AND FILLED IT WITH WATER.   

417
00:16:43,937 --> 00:16:45,636
            IT'S A GIFT FOR YOU.

418
00:16:45,638 --> 00:16:47,805
                  YOU KNOW,     
      'CAUSE WATER'S YOUR THING.

419
00:16:47,807 --> 00:16:49,440
                [ CHUCKLES ]    
             PRETTY GOOD, RIGHT?

420
00:16:49,442 --> 00:16:51,275
             THE BARN'S OUT HERE
               IN THE COUNTRY,  

421
00:16:51,277 --> 00:16:53,845
             BUT NOW YOU CAN GET
     YOUR MOISTURE FIX WHENEVER.

422
00:16:53,847 --> 00:16:56,214
                 DO ALL THAT    
             WATER STUFF YOU DO.

423
00:16:56,216 --> 00:16:58,149
       WATER?                   

424
00:16:58,151 --> 00:16:59,851
     SERIOUSLY?                 

425
00:16:59,853 --> 00:17:00,718
                    YEAH!       

426
00:17:00,720 --> 00:17:02,153
   YOU DO REALIZE               
    THAT I SPENT                

427
00:17:02,155 --> 00:17:05,056
THE LAST FEW MONTHS TRAPPED     
UNDER THE OCEAN, RIGHT?         

428
00:17:05,058 --> 00:17:07,392
                    SURE!       
              BUT I THOUGHT --  

429
00:17:07,394 --> 00:17:10,661
 IT WAS AN ENDLESS,             
 CRUSHING DARKNESS.             

430
00:17:10,663 --> 00:17:13,965
    WET AND BLEAK               
  AND SUFFOCATING.              

431
00:17:13,967 --> 00:17:19,037
WATER WAS THE TOMB I LIVED IN   
  FOR THOSE MONTHS.             

432
00:17:20,974 --> 00:17:23,808
               TOMB, YOU SAY?   

433
00:17:23,810 --> 00:17:24,909
        YEAH.                   

434
00:17:24,911 --> 00:17:27,311
I'M KIND OF TAKING A BREAK      
FROM WATER RIGHT NOW.           

435
00:17:27,313 --> 00:17:30,181
    BUT THANKS...               
    FOR THE LAKE.               

436
00:17:30,183 --> 00:17:31,382
              UHH.              

437
00:17:31,384 --> 00:17:32,917
                 [ GROANS ]     

438
00:17:32,919 --> 00:17:36,154
DON'T WORRY, STEVEN.            
IT'S NOT YOUR FAULT.            

439
00:17:39,426 --> 00:17:41,426
        Peridot: A POOL!        

440
00:17:41,428 --> 00:17:42,927
 WHAT A CLODDY IDEA.            

441
00:17:42,929 --> 00:17:44,662
      OF COURSE                 
SHE WOULDN'T LIKE THAT.         

442
00:17:44,664 --> 00:17:46,431
  THERE'S NOTHING!              
      NOTHING!                  

443
00:17:46,433 --> 00:17:47,665
      NOTHING!                  

444
00:17:47,667 --> 00:17:49,400
      THERE HAS TO BE SOMETHING.

445
00:17:49,402 --> 00:17:51,235
           SOMETHING, SOMETHING.

446
00:17:51,237 --> 00:17:54,572
           MAYBE, UH, INSTEAD OF
            SOMETHING<i> SHE</i> LIKES,

447
00:17:54,574 --> 00:17:57,075
             GIVE HER SOMETHING 
